30:06.214 --> 30:08.777
It's interesting you ask that question. I was 
elected the most popular student in my senior

30:08.797 --> 30:14.725
class band. And surprisingly, the girl I was going 
with was elected the most popular girl. And the way

30:20.312 --> 30:28.963
they put it, though, is the one most likely to 
succeed and best liked by his fellow students. the

30:30.563 --> 30:31.604
way they described it. And I'll never forget it as 
long as I live. And I'm impressed with what you're

30:34.768 --> 30:39.334
doing on the team. My picture was published in the 
front page of Dallas Morning News that day. I bet

30:46.664 --> 30:49.127
you have a copy of that around the house someplace. 
I have a picture in one of my albums someplace. Now,

30:54.334 --> 31:00.081
it seems to me then that when you graduated from 
high school, you had some firm goals. Is that true?

31:02.397 --> 31:08.044
Yes, when I graduated from high school, I 
definitely wanted college education, and I

31:02.397 --> 31:08.044
wanted to go to Texas A&M. That was in 1933. But the 
influence of my father again, the pressure, if you

31:10.206 --> 31:28.667
will, to work, and the fact that he couldn't or 
wouldn't help And he really couldn't help

31:29.828 --> 31:35.734
financially to send me to college, because they 
had other kids to take care of, too. I just knew I was

31:37.495 --> 31:39.557
going to have to work for a while. And it was in... 
Did you ever think about applying for

31:40.158 --> 31:46.504
scholarships to any universities?

31:48.285 --> 31:53.130
I really didn't have anything to establish the 
basis for a scholarship, except good grades. I

31:54.551 --> 31:55.252
didn't do it. I think it might have been because I 
figured I was going to have to work a while to help

31:58.060 --> 32:01.785
the family. Why did you think that you wanted to go 
to Texas A&M instead of some other university?

32:08.194 --> 32:11.058
Well, Texas A&M was one thing, was military 
school. Sure. And I couldn't get a congressional

32:11.980 --> 32:17.047
appointment to go to West Point. Yeah. And at least 
I'd be able to take military, and I just liked what I

32:18.229 --> 32:26.380
had learned about colleges compared to all of 
them, but I just want to go to Texas A&M. It's a band

32:31.603 --> 32:32.865
school. You just liked what you heard about it. 
Right, right. Now, let's talk about the

32:38.752 --> 32:40.554
Depression. You said that the Depression had an 
impact on your life. Would you explain that?

32:47.942 --> 32:56.232
Well, when you live in a crowded house, and 
sometimes all you have at night is lot of beans and

32:56.701 --> 33:26.353
if you get in late the other kids have eaten more 
than their share and not much left and when you have

32:56.701 --> 33:26.353
to sleep in a bed with as a young kid now this was in 
1929 let's say I was 14 years old maybe have to sleep

32:56.701 --> 33:26.353
in even in the same bed with your sister in a bedroom 
with two other beds with some other kids in it, and

33:26.519 --> 33:56.020
having an outside toilet, no indoor sewage 
facilities, and in a kitchen where my mother had no

33:26.519 --> 33:56.020
modern sink to work out of, had to carry water from 
outside, and

33:26.519 --> 33:56.020
having to go out and chop wood to put in the stove for 
heat and for cooking. and sometimes it seemed that

33:56.742 --> 34:01.087
I was the only boy to do it.

34:06.993 --> 34:23.391
Having the lights turned off because you can't pay 
the bill, having the phone cut up because you can't

34:06.993 --> 34:23.391
pay the bill,

34:06.993 --> 34:23.391
not being able to pay the doctor bills, seeing my 
sisters and brothers go with teeth that needed

34:24.569 --> 34:32.118
fixing and seeing my fellow students having their 
teeth fixed and my sister's brother's not. All of

34:33.459 --> 34:41.449
these things make an impression on me.

34:41.809 --> 34:43.671
What was that impression? You want to do better. 
You want to get out of it. You know you can do better.

34:51.781 --> 34:52.922
Detecting a feeling from my relatives, who were 
better off than my mother and father on both sides,

34:54.067 --> 35:08.604
particularly my father's side, where they looked 
down on my family, even my, looked down even on my

34:54.067 --> 35:08.604
father, his own brother and sister did.

35:10.206 --> 35:12.429
These things left an imprint on me. I guess all of 
these things made me quite an analytical type of a

35:14.071 --> 35:21.660
person, even in my young teens. into why these, why 
this, why so forth and so forth, and having to

35:23.092 --> 35:49.858
submit and work while my fellow students played 
and had money to go to shows and so forth,

35:23.092 --> 35:49.858
not being able to dress well enough to even have 
dates really living a little bit in chain all of

35:50.378 --> 36:05.755
these things have an impact and there are all of 
these things all the economic conditions did you

35:50.378 --> 36:05.755
say that your father had a hard time finding work 
during the Depression? So it got worse during the

36:08.909 --> 36:11.072
Depression? Yes. Oh, yes. You said 1929, of 
course, that's when the Depression starts, but it

36:13.034 --> 36:18.659
really hits the balls in 1932. Well, 32 and 33, 
that's right. And it was in 1929, 1933, you see that

36:23.264 --> 36:28.790
I was in high school. And like I say, I had my 
friends, parents, not provided the money to buy my

36:32.718 --> 36:43.233
uniform, particularly those boots, costly 
boots, a uniform which you wore every day to go to

36:32.718 --> 36:43.233
high school. I am sure, I'm almost sure, I had to 
drop out of high school because I wouldn't have

36:43.654 --> 36:53.208
clothes

36:43.654 --> 36:53.208
to wear. My dad didn't have enough money to, 
sometimes you've got to work for a week or so. And

36:58.275 --> 37:00.919
living from day to day, He wouldn't give me, some 
mornings even, you know, upset, my dad wouldn't

37:02.097 --> 37:18.997
even give me the fifteen cents for lunch money that 
I would use to buy, you know, maybe a hamburger and a

37:02.097 --> 37:18.997
glass of milk for lunch. Sometimes he's irate at me 
because I wouldn't quit school. He wouldn't give

37:23.061 --> 37:24.343
me the fifteen cents. But nevertheless, somehow 
or another, I always managed to have seven cents 14

37:30.245 --> 37:34.752
cents, 7 cents to come back on car fare in my last 
year in high school.

37:38.698 --> 37:49.494
Many people were poverty stricken in our 
environment where we lived during the

37:38.698 --> 37:49.494
Depression.

37:52.378 --> 37:55.623
But it seemed like we were always worse off. My dad 
was not a good manager. He was a selfish person, and

37:57.481 --> 38:05.893
he'd spend money on his car before he'd spend money 
on some of us kids. What did your mother think about

38:05.913 --> 38:07.936
it? My mother and father thought an awful lot about 
this. Her philosophy was, I guess I got my basic

38:11.422 --> 38:17.751
philosophy from my mother, sacrifice and so 
forth. But she and my father clashed an awful lot.

38:22.057 --> 38:26.041
And of course, the environment is what made it that 
way, not enough to go around. And my mother

38:26.401 --> 38:28.803
probably didn't get along well at all. And of 
course, it's another thing I observed. Sure. Did

38:34.008 --> 38:38.993
your father ever accept, or did your family ever 
accept any federal help? Because this is the time

38:39.013 --> 38:44.278
that Franklin Roosevelt comes in and establishes 
the New Deal.

38:48.308 --> 38:55.118
My father definitely would take any handout he 
could get and wasn't ashamed of it at all. And so he

38:56.040 --> 38:57.822
accepted federal funds? Yes. Well, I don't 
remember any particular federal funds at that

38:58.704 --> 39:03.230
time, like food stamps as they are today. But it 
seemed like there was some sort of an organization

39:05.374 --> 39:12.885
where he actually went down and got food. I can't 
remember this very well. But I do need church or

39:15.545 --> 39:19.489
some YMCA or Salvation Army or something. No, we 
never got any help from that. Through my mother's

39:21.911 --> 39:37.125
religious zeal to keep us kids in church, the 
minister would come to see us, but I don't remember

39:21.911 --> 39:37.125
ever any financial help from a church or any YMCA 
organization.

39:39.708 --> 39:41.890
My neighbors would help, yes. My relatives, 
particularly my favorite Uncle John, dad's

39:42.173 --> 39:50.502
brother, who was a court reporter at that time, he 
would help a lot. And I became the pride and joy of

39:50.522 --> 39:56.948
his life when I graduated from high school with 
honors.

40:02.814 --> 40:04.436
It was hard, hard times. Did your father ever work 
for the WPA or the CCCs or anything like that? No,

40:10.182 --> 40:10.442
no. And to carry on and answer your question, I 
remember it was in 1936 and 37, through the Home

40:11.097 --> 40:25.256
Owners Loan Corporation, where they helped 
people pay for their home.

40:29.601 --> 40:40.716
My dad, through a job he had with a southwestern 
life insurance company man, painting houses,

40:41.371 --> 40:48.820
buy a house in Oak Cliff at quite a reduced price. 
And immediately thereafter, it was obvious he

40:49.220 --> 40:54.947
couldn't make the payments. The payments were $37 
and $50. No, the payments were $50 a month. And I

41:03.738 --> 41:11.327
remember taking a job with the US Treasury 
dispersing office in 1938.

41:15.307 --> 41:17.711
six, and seven. And I would pay those payments on 
that home. That's the only way we could keep that

41:20.114 --> 41:21.837
home. You made that much money? I made $37.50 every 
two weeks. And I would take $25 each two weeks and

41:26.864 --> 41:35.557
keep up the payments on that. Whenever he failed, I 
would make the payments. That's the only way we

41:37.660 --> 41:40.344
kept that home for a while. How long did you keep 
that home? We kept that home until I... left went to

41:45.142 --> 42:13.326
the flying cadets and uh was away from home of 
course and military and then my dad lost it he could

41:45.142 --> 42:13.326
no longer make those payments

41:45.142 --> 42:13.326
what what political party did he vote for i guess my 
dad today painted grave was still a democrat uh did

41:45.142 --> 42:13.326
he support franklin roosevelt i he He talked 
openly about supporting the president, but I

42:13.627 --> 42:23.857
doubt, seriously, my dad and mother ever voted in 
their entire life. But he was definitely a

42:23.877 --> 42:25.579
Democrat. Hated the Republicans. To him, the 
Republican was a rich man's party. The Democrat

42:29.483 --> 42:31.284
was a poor man's party. Therefore, I'm a Democrat. 
Did that have any influence on your political

42:33.667 --> 42:36.469
philosophy? Looking back, no. Today, I'd call 
myself, really, if you will, more of an

42:43.900 --> 42:47.564
independent, I've always thought for myself. Of 
course, in the military life, you know, it's a

42:47.644 --> 43:05.362
little bit different, but I'd call myself more of 
an independent, definitely, absolutely, and

42:47.644 --> 43:05.362
absolutely a conservative, assuming the 
conservative and the old, you know, definition. A

43:07.164 --> 43:11.629
conservative on what issues? Every issue you can 
think of. I think that the Social Security Act,

43:13.390 --> 43:42.105
although conceived probably in the right spirit 
at the time of the Roosevelt administration, is

43:13.390 --> 43:42.105
probably today one of the worst things that could 
have happened to this country from the standpoint

43:13.390 --> 43:42.105
of our democratic system and the old system in the 
United States, the economy where a man has a chance

43:13.390 --> 43:42.105
to work. make a living. I think it's, I think in 
concept, it is a horrible thing.

43:51.811 --> 43:53.472
And I'm drawing it. And you're drawing it. And I'm 
drawing it. Do you see any inconsistency there?

43:57.877 --> 43:58.517
Nope. I paid them.

